00:00:26.157 --> 00:00:27.990
STEPHEN PEARSE: How
many of you guys in here

00:00:27.990 --> 00:00:30.970
think you might want to one
day run your own company

00:00:30.970 --> 00:00:35.230
or begin a startup?

00:00:35.230 --> 00:00:37.480
The vast majority of you.

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:38.630
Good.

00:00:38.630 --> 00:00:42.500
Remember that, because at
the end of my presentation,

00:00:42.500 --> 00:00:45.030
I'm going to give you guys
an opportunity to begin

00:00:45.030 --> 00:00:46.730
that process.

00:00:46.730 --> 00:00:54.540
My name is Steve Pearse and
my background, let's see.

00:00:54.540 --> 00:00:59.940
Former CEO, entrepreneur,
I am an angel investor.

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:04.280
I work with venture capital
companies as a litmus test.

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:06.820
If I like it, they
might like it too.

00:01:06.820 --> 00:01:10.420
And I advise CEOs and startups.

00:01:10.420 --> 00:01:15.457
I live in Colorado, Florida,
I used to live here full-time,

00:01:15.457 --> 00:01:16.540
now I just come and visit.

00:01:19.050 --> 00:01:23.740
So my specialty and background,
primarily telecommunications,

00:01:23.740 --> 00:01:28.770
IT, and as of late, the last
10 years or so, health science.

00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:32.790
I've bought companies,
I have sold companies.

00:01:32.790 --> 00:01:37.160
I have raised over $250
million over six rounds,

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:41.600
and my background is kind
of up through the ranks.

00:01:41.600 --> 00:01:44.890
AT&amp;T, then I became
chief engineer at Sprint,

00:01:44.890 --> 00:01:48.890
ran operations and started
Time Warner Telecom,

00:01:48.890 --> 00:01:53.490
I ran a wireless company, was an
executive vice president at Bay

00:01:53.490 --> 00:01:57.320
Networks, merged into
Nortel in a successful sale

00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:59.230
for $7 billion.

00:01:59.230 --> 00:02:02.090
And then I did my own
startup in Silicon Valley,

00:02:02.090 --> 00:02:04.440
and that was cool.

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:08.949
That, I came in when we
were valued at $18 million,

00:02:08.949 --> 00:02:14.740
and we sold for $2.7 billion
less than a year and a half-ish

00:02:14.740 --> 00:02:16.460
later.

00:02:16.460 --> 00:02:18.910
Those were the days.

00:02:18.910 --> 00:02:21.070
You might think
that was a bubble.

00:02:21.070 --> 00:02:21.920
Guess what?

00:02:21.920 --> 00:02:24.080
There's always a bubble.

00:02:24.080 --> 00:02:25.370
There's always a bubble.

00:02:25.370 --> 00:02:28.270
Look what's happening now with
Twitter and social networking.

00:02:28.270 --> 00:02:29.960
There's always a bubble.

00:02:29.960 --> 00:02:33.960
Your challenge is to find
how can I make my own bubble,

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:35.880
or where is the next
bubble going to be.

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:38.510
Your challenge is to
be a hockey player

00:02:38.510 --> 00:02:43.230
and skate to where the
puck is going to be,

00:02:43.230 --> 00:02:45.730
not where it is now,
because you're too late.

00:02:45.730 --> 00:02:49.040
Where do you think that next
big event is going to happen?

00:02:49.040 --> 00:02:49.956
That's your challenge.

00:02:56.620 --> 00:02:59.030
The startup.

00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:03.100
And these statistics
are about right.

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:05.860
Some might say
I'm over-generous,

00:03:05.860 --> 00:03:09.970
but out of every 10 startups,
maybe one will succeed.

00:03:09.970 --> 00:03:12.400
Kawasaki will say one out of 20.

00:03:12.400 --> 00:03:14.050
But one out of 10 will succeed.

00:03:14.050 --> 00:03:15.394
What's a success?

00:03:15.394 --> 00:03:18.470
Success is, if
you're an investor,

00:03:18.470 --> 00:03:21.230
you make at least 10x.

00:03:21.230 --> 00:03:24.600
The investor really
wants 100x, and they're

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:27.760
going to gun for that,
but they'll take 10x.

00:03:27.760 --> 00:03:30.180
They want something that's
going to make-- it's called,

00:03:30.180 --> 00:03:33.220
hey this company, thanks,
Steve, you made the fund.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:34.880
What does that mean,
I made the fund?

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:37.260
They've got a fund, they have
a lot of private investors

00:03:37.260 --> 00:03:40.540
give them their money,
they invest that money,

00:03:40.540 --> 00:03:44.600
and they want all that
money back, plus more

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:46.390
to the investors.

00:03:46.390 --> 00:03:49.330
If you have a $100
million fund, you've

00:03:49.330 --> 00:03:53.470
got to give that $100 million
back or you're a failure.

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:58.290
You really want to give $200
million back, $400 million

00:03:58.290 --> 00:03:58.790
back.

00:03:58.790 --> 00:04:00.830
You want to give
much, much, much more,

00:04:00.830 --> 00:04:02.360
and as a venture
capitalist, you get

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:05.200
to pocket an even
bigger percentage

00:04:05.200 --> 00:04:08.760
than your limited partners
or investors will take.

00:04:08.760 --> 00:04:12.810
So they want a 10x company
that makes the fund.

00:04:12.810 --> 00:04:18.000
So 10 companies, they want one
to be a factor of 10 better.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.320
Three out of 10-ish might
yield a moderate return.

00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:23.460
What's a moderate return?

00:04:23.460 --> 00:04:27.630
Maybe 2 to 4x in
four to seven years.

00:04:27.630 --> 00:04:30.190
And you really want
to be shutting down

00:04:30.190 --> 00:04:32.620
the fund in about seven years.

00:04:32.620 --> 00:04:35.330
Sometimes it happens,
sometimes it doesn't.

00:04:35.330 --> 00:04:39.610
And then six are failures,
completely shut down.

00:04:39.610 --> 00:04:43.360
So that's the odds
you're facing here.

00:04:43.360 --> 00:04:46.930
You might think, oh
God, if I do this,

00:04:46.930 --> 00:04:51.900
chances are I'm not going to
be a success, a big success.

00:04:51.900 --> 00:04:57.020
That's fine, because
investors know these odds,

00:04:57.020 --> 00:05:01.280
and if you come from a failure
or two, there's no problem.

00:05:01.280 --> 00:05:04.080
As long as you did
a good job, you

00:05:04.080 --> 00:05:06.650
learn from the
failures or mistake.

00:05:06.650 --> 00:05:09.250
Maybe it was just the wrong
bid at the wrong time.

00:05:09.250 --> 00:05:12.280
But they're not afraid
of reinvesting in people

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:13.582
who have done this a few times.

00:05:13.582 --> 00:05:14.540
And look at the Valley.

00:05:14.540 --> 00:05:16.720
You have people
skip companies right

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:17.960
and left all over the place.

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:21.630
So long history of backgrounds.

00:05:21.630 --> 00:05:23.980
OK.

00:05:23.980 --> 00:05:26.160
Why do a startup?

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:28.600
I mean, what's the game here?

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:32.700
What are you trying to play?

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:36.920
Well, if you do a startup, and
you get money from investors,

00:05:36.920 --> 00:05:39.680
you have to be able to exit.

00:05:39.680 --> 00:05:40.690
And what is an exit?

00:05:40.690 --> 00:05:44.490
You have to either go
public or get sold.

00:05:44.490 --> 00:05:45.590
That's an exit.

00:05:45.590 --> 00:05:47.020
Why is going public an exit?

00:05:47.020 --> 00:05:50.360
Because finally, I can
cash out the stocks

00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:52.600
that I bought from
you a long time ago.

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:54.850
Your investors want
their money back.

00:05:54.850 --> 00:05:57.160
If you're interested in
running a mom and pop

00:05:57.160 --> 00:05:59.470
business with a cool
idea and cool technology,

00:05:59.470 --> 00:06:02.940
no one's going to invest
in it except family.

00:06:02.940 --> 00:06:03.660
Why?

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:05.826
Because they're never going
to get their money back.

00:06:05.826 --> 00:06:08.090
It's not a liquid asset.

00:06:08.090 --> 00:06:14.220
So you have to plan on going
public or getting sold.

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:18.790
If you're a technology company--
and by the way, officially,

00:06:18.790 --> 00:06:23.880
the answer is always
I'm going public.

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:25.020
I'm not going to sell.

00:06:25.020 --> 00:06:26.750
Never going to sell.

00:06:26.750 --> 00:06:30.210
I'm going to run this thing
forever, hand it off to the--

00:06:30.210 --> 00:06:32.380
why do you have to say that?

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:37.120
Why do you have to say we're
not going to get acquired?

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:41.060
Because if you say I'm going to
get acquired, you're not in it.

00:06:41.060 --> 00:06:42.510
Your heart's not in it.

00:06:42.510 --> 00:06:45.850
You're looking for a
trick, a magic pony,

00:06:45.850 --> 00:06:48.140
I want to sell this puppy,
I'm going to make a buck,

00:06:48.140 --> 00:06:51.497
and I don't want to-- I want
to sell it and make money

00:06:51.497 --> 00:06:52.080
and that's it.

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:52.871
No, no, no, no, no.

00:06:52.871 --> 00:06:55.370
You can't say that.

00:06:55.370 --> 00:06:59.120
You say that and no one's
going to give you a penny.

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:02.010
So you're always going public.

00:07:02.010 --> 00:07:04.000
But why would a company
ever want to buy you,

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:07.540
just in case they
wanted to buy you?

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:09.650
Bay Networks.

00:07:09.650 --> 00:07:12.570
At one time, Bay Networks
was bigger than Cisco.

00:07:12.570 --> 00:07:15.860
Bay built routers.

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:18.080
Internet IP routers.

00:07:18.080 --> 00:07:22.800
And I ran the internet and
telecom business group.

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:27.670
And we built blades to replace
the old technology that

00:07:27.670 --> 00:07:30.750
was maybe 10 megabits a second.

00:07:30.750 --> 00:07:34.980
We had to come out with 100
megabit a second, and then gig,

00:07:34.980 --> 00:07:36.470
and play that game.

00:07:36.470 --> 00:07:38.300
Different interfaces.

00:07:38.300 --> 00:07:41.540
And my team was a good team.

00:07:41.540 --> 00:07:46.830
We could build a blade
in about 18 months.

00:07:46.830 --> 00:07:48.560
That was pretty good.

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:52.550
People working maybe
9:00-5:00, 9:00-6:00.

00:07:52.550 --> 00:07:56.450
Good engineers, teamwork,
meetings, stuff like that.

00:07:56.450 --> 00:07:59.620
A startup can do
that in nine months.

00:07:59.620 --> 00:08:03.490
And nine months' delta in
a new product introduction

00:08:03.490 --> 00:08:07.440
can spell the difference
between failure and success

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:08.170
in this business.

00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:14.100
I could not afford to
build a new blade that

00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:18.730
goes into my rack and
sell it to my customers,

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:22.300
sometimes, if I can
only do it in 18 months.

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:25.250
If I have another
company start advertising

00:08:25.250 --> 00:08:27.440
and have a good marketing
person and they're

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:30.510
telling the industry analysts
and all the industry rags,

00:08:30.510 --> 00:08:31.940
hey we got this new widget.

00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:34.799
And it's got 100 megabits now.

00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:37.730
And we're selling and
customers love it.

00:08:37.730 --> 00:08:40.100
I have to do a make
or buy decision.

00:08:40.100 --> 00:08:42.030
I may interrupt my development.

00:08:42.030 --> 00:08:45.920
I may say, finance,
go strike a deal.

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:48.160
Let's buy this company quickly.

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:50.360
And Bay did that all the time.

00:08:50.360 --> 00:08:54.170
I bought a bunch of
startups, hot startups

00:08:54.170 --> 00:08:56.490
for internet dial-in modems.

00:08:56.490 --> 00:08:59.390
That was big time
back in the '90s.

00:08:59.390 --> 00:09:03.620
So you had a box that was 10
times smaller, faster, cheaper,

00:09:03.620 --> 00:09:07.100
all that stuff, using
chips that just came off

00:09:07.100 --> 00:09:09.829
the line from Intel
or TI or whatever,

00:09:09.829 --> 00:09:11.620
and you can build
something in nine months,

00:09:11.620 --> 00:09:13.710
I'd buy that company.

00:09:13.710 --> 00:09:17.190
That's a great example
of how you can go out,

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:21.080
take the state-of-the-art
today, the latest chip sets,

00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:25.050
build it smarter
smaller, faster,

00:09:25.050 --> 00:09:28.030
all these nice characteristics,
and sell your company.

00:09:28.030 --> 00:09:31.040
And you can do it over
and over and over again.

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:33.160
Why can you do
that as a startup?

00:09:33.160 --> 00:09:35.490
Why can't big companies do that?

00:09:35.490 --> 00:09:39.870
Because you're
working for stock.

00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:42.590
You're not working
for a promotion,

00:09:42.590 --> 00:09:44.620
you're not working
for a lot of things

00:09:44.620 --> 00:09:46.430
big companies' people work for.

00:09:46.430 --> 00:09:48.280
A nice stable lifestyle.

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:51.840
You're willing to work until
midnight and bring in pizza.

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:57.130
The CEO, when I was a CEO, I'd
bring in Chinese just to entice

00:09:57.130 --> 00:10:00.670
people, please stay
longer and work harder.

00:10:00.670 --> 00:10:02.740
Because everybody's
working for the same thing.

00:10:02.740 --> 00:10:04.080
Everybody wants to get rich.

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:06.590
Everybody wants stock.

00:10:06.590 --> 00:10:07.893
It's a great unifier.

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:13.960
It is the enticement
that makes everybody

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:16.360
think along the same way.

00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:19.850
When I was at AT&amp;T,
everybody wanted

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:24.080
to make you look bad so
they might step on you

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:26.940
and get another
$5,000 raise, or maybe

00:10:26.940 --> 00:10:29.750
run the department
with five more people.

00:10:29.750 --> 00:10:31.880
That's big company mentality.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:34.620
Startups were such
a great cleanse

00:10:34.620 --> 00:10:37.070
when I left the big
corporate environment

00:10:37.070 --> 00:10:38.779
and went to the startup world.

00:10:38.779 --> 00:10:40.320
That's what we're
talking about here.

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:42.824
That's the taste of what
could be your future.

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:51.350
OK, getting money.

00:10:51.350 --> 00:10:53.310
Signal to noise.

00:10:53.310 --> 00:10:55.100
Signal to noise.

00:10:55.100 --> 00:10:58.400
Do you know how much noise
is out there that you're

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:02.470
going to be fighting against,
if you want attention

00:11:02.470 --> 00:11:03.380
as a startup?

00:11:03.380 --> 00:11:07.310
If you want attention
from a VC or an angel,

00:11:07.310 --> 00:11:12.000
you're wading through a
tremendous amount of noise.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.456
Your signal has to
be muy powerful.

00:11:16.456 --> 00:11:17.830
And we're going
to talk about how

00:11:17.830 --> 00:11:20.190
to make your signal
very powerful,

00:11:20.190 --> 00:11:22.130
and punching through that noise.

00:11:22.130 --> 00:11:25.530
Because you've got to go out
and grab people by the neck,

00:11:25.530 --> 00:11:30.140
shake them, and make them
listen to your pitch.

00:11:30.140 --> 00:11:33.460
So, this is a terrible
elevator pitch,

00:11:33.460 --> 00:11:37.810
but it's the elements of what
you want to be looking for.

00:11:37.810 --> 00:11:39.220
I'm going to paraphrase.

00:11:39.220 --> 00:11:42.190
For this huge,
great target market

00:11:42.190 --> 00:11:46.060
who really hate the
stuff they're using now,

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:51.620
our thermostat is a new
[? Heigelberg ?] category

00:11:51.620 --> 00:11:55.750
that provides all your solutions
you've been looking for.

00:11:55.750 --> 00:11:59.700
Unlike the bozos who
we're competing against,

00:11:59.700 --> 00:12:03.250
we have assembled
incredible, groundbreaking

00:12:03.250 --> 00:12:07.569
technology that is going
to be ready in six months.

00:12:07.569 --> 00:12:09.860
Essentially, that's kind of
what you want to be saying.

00:12:09.860 --> 00:12:12.110
You have to have all these
elements in your elevator

00:12:12.110 --> 00:12:13.980
pitch.

00:12:13.980 --> 00:12:18.130
And say it a lot better
than this format up here.

00:12:18.130 --> 00:12:20.120
That's what you need to do.

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:22.950
I'd like you to start
thinking about filling

00:12:22.950 --> 00:12:26.040
in the blanks for
your ideas now.

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:29.790
Whether or not it's a real
product or technology,

00:12:29.790 --> 00:12:31.320
or something you
think, hey, this

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:33.760
would be cool if I
could ever do this.

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:38.260
Think about how
you would say this.

00:12:38.260 --> 00:12:41.870
Because that's the elevator
pitch and will determine

00:12:41.870 --> 00:12:45.120
your readiness to do a startup.

00:12:45.120 --> 00:12:47.850
Your readiness to get money.

00:12:47.850 --> 00:12:51.760
You've got really one shot,
because once a venture

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:55.320
capitalist has seen your face,
and you've said a few words,

00:12:55.320 --> 00:12:57.212
they're either
thinking right away,

00:12:57.212 --> 00:12:59.420
I'm going to go ahead and
listen to the rest of this,

00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:03.800
or you're having trouble
here, and then you're gone.

00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:04.810
Why?

00:13:04.810 --> 00:13:05.900
Too much noise.

00:13:05.900 --> 00:13:09.360
They see thousands of pitches
and thousands of people,

00:13:09.360 --> 00:13:13.250
and they have to quickly-- it's
almost neuronally implanted.

00:13:13.250 --> 00:13:17.610
They can very quickly determine
whether you're worth it or not.

00:13:17.610 --> 00:13:20.420
So that's why it's important
to rehearse this stuff

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:21.501
and get it down right.

00:13:24.530 --> 00:13:26.302
Everybody's maybe heard this.

00:13:26.302 --> 00:13:28.260
I didn't have time to
write you a short letter,

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:31.530
so I wrote you a long one.

00:13:31.530 --> 00:13:32.880
What does that mean?

00:13:32.880 --> 00:13:37.470
It means you've got to
be super, super crisp.

00:13:37.470 --> 00:13:39.340
You've got to be able
to say what you're

00:13:39.340 --> 00:13:41.900
going to say and enunciate it.

00:13:41.900 --> 00:13:45.900
Grab them-- you have to hit
him over the head with a hammer

00:13:45.900 --> 00:13:46.950
with what you're saying.

00:13:46.950 --> 00:13:50.470
It's got to be so compelling.

00:13:50.470 --> 00:13:53.210
We'll talk more about
that, but you really

00:13:53.210 --> 00:13:56.240
got to capture their attention.

00:13:56.240 --> 00:13:59.020
And then Jeffrey Moore.

00:14:03.280 --> 00:14:05.360
What do you mean, you
have to induce greed?

00:14:05.360 --> 00:14:07.190
Greed doesn't sound good.

00:14:07.190 --> 00:14:12.690
Well, when you go to the store
and you see something on sale,

00:14:12.690 --> 00:14:14.190
what are you thinking?

00:14:14.190 --> 00:14:16.710
You're thinking that's on sale.

00:14:16.710 --> 00:14:17.510
Do I need it?

00:14:17.510 --> 00:14:18.490
I don't know.

00:14:18.490 --> 00:14:22.280
Maybe I should buy it
now while it's on sale.

00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:25.760
You're inducing
spontaneous greed

00:14:25.760 --> 00:14:30.490
when you buy something for
sale, because it's a good deal.

00:14:30.490 --> 00:14:32.290
Might not be there later.

00:14:32.290 --> 00:14:35.740
You have to induce greed on the
part of your investors venture

00:14:35.740 --> 00:14:40.020
catalysts or angel
investors, even family.

00:14:40.020 --> 00:14:43.100
You have to say I'm on
to something really big.

00:14:43.100 --> 00:14:44.050
Really, really big.

00:14:44.050 --> 00:14:46.780
This is going to be
huge, and you need

00:14:46.780 --> 00:14:49.720
to think about investing now.

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:51.740
You have to get
that greed going,

00:14:51.740 --> 00:14:54.950
and that greed has to be started
from the very first elevator

00:14:54.950 --> 00:14:55.730
pitch.

00:14:55.730 --> 00:14:57.170
And really, a good
elevator pitch

00:14:57.170 --> 00:14:58.760
isn't what I just said up here.

00:14:58.760 --> 00:15:00.820
A good elevator pitch
starts with a hook.

00:15:00.820 --> 00:15:05.510
And we're going to talk about
that hook a little bit later.

00:15:05.510 --> 00:15:07.250
The pitch.

00:15:07.250 --> 00:15:08.430
Keep it simple.

00:15:08.430 --> 00:15:10.510
Keep it simple and stupid.

00:15:10.510 --> 00:15:12.450
Keep it really, really simple.

00:15:12.450 --> 00:15:14.800
No matter how simple
you think your pitch is,

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:20.445
no matter how easy and clear
you think you are, you're not.

00:15:20.445 --> 00:15:22.800
You're not being clear enough.

00:15:22.800 --> 00:15:25.250
You need to really dumb it down.

00:15:25.250 --> 00:15:26.360
Like third grade.

00:15:26.360 --> 00:15:28.784
You need to be able to
explain it to a third grader.

00:15:28.784 --> 00:15:30.450
If you can explain
it to a third grader,

00:15:30.450 --> 00:15:32.190
you're doing a good job.

00:15:32.190 --> 00:15:35.820
Don't worry about coming
across as too simplistic.

00:15:35.820 --> 00:15:38.970
They'll pull you up
to a different level

00:15:38.970 --> 00:15:42.327
if they need to, like, let's
talk more about the technology,

00:15:42.327 --> 00:15:43.910
let's get into the
weeds a little bit.

00:15:43.910 --> 00:15:47.210
But if you lose them early on
by being too technical or too

00:15:47.210 --> 00:15:49.230
complex, you're gone.

00:15:49.230 --> 00:15:52.130
They won't give you the chance
of explaining yourself later,

00:15:52.130 --> 00:15:54.540
because you weren't able
to communicate effectively

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:57.330
up front.

00:15:57.330 --> 00:16:05.980
This hook is kind of like a pain
point, or a statement of greed.

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:09.870
You have to say something
that is so exciting, they're

00:16:09.870 --> 00:16:12.520
going to stop what they're doing
and continue to listen to you,

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:13.894
because I've never
heard of that.

00:16:13.894 --> 00:16:16.020
How is that possible?

00:16:16.020 --> 00:16:17.480
Think about your
target audience.

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:19.260
Is your target
audience technical?

00:16:19.260 --> 00:16:21.894
Is your target audience
a lay consumer?

00:16:21.894 --> 00:16:24.060
Is it the financial analysts
who don't know anything

00:16:24.060 --> 00:16:27.340
about technology, they want to
hear about money and numbers.

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:30.220
You need to really understand
who your target audience is.

00:16:30.220 --> 00:16:32.350
If the eyes start to
glaze over, you failed.

00:16:32.350 --> 00:16:33.780
You didn't do your homework.

00:16:33.780 --> 00:16:35.810
You didn't understand
who your audience was.

00:16:35.810 --> 00:16:37.290
Talk to them on their level.

00:16:37.290 --> 00:16:38.770
That makes them excited.

00:16:38.770 --> 00:16:42.500
Everybody's listening to
you, greedy for something.

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:45.320
Give them what they want.

00:16:45.320 --> 00:16:49.300
And if you're in a room
of different people,

00:16:49.300 --> 00:16:53.900
change your pitch to the
lowest common denominator

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:57.620
You might have a room full of
VCs and a couple of junior VCs.

00:16:57.620 --> 00:17:01.340
If one of the
partners in the room

00:17:01.340 --> 00:17:04.220
is not from this
industry at all,

00:17:04.220 --> 00:17:07.960
you need to lower it down
to that person's level,

00:17:07.960 --> 00:17:09.859
because if you lose
that person, they're

00:17:09.859 --> 00:17:11.150
going to blackball you later.

00:17:11.150 --> 00:17:14.042
They're going to
say, they lost me.

00:17:14.042 --> 00:17:15.750
They weren't able to
communicate with me.

00:17:15.750 --> 00:17:17.099
I don't like them.

00:17:17.099 --> 00:17:20.940
So be sure, when you're
scanning the room,

00:17:20.940 --> 00:17:23.390
or before you even
walk into the room,

00:17:23.390 --> 00:17:27.609
get a list of who
the VCs may attend,

00:17:27.609 --> 00:17:31.790
what their backgrounds are,
what companies they work for.

00:17:31.790 --> 00:17:34.220
If you can connect
with any of them

00:17:34.220 --> 00:17:36.950
by their past history
with a person or a company

00:17:36.950 --> 00:17:39.680
that you're familiar
with, bring it in.

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:42.730
Say, by the way, I happen to
know you were from Nortel.

00:17:42.730 --> 00:17:44.550
Did you know so and so?

00:17:44.550 --> 00:17:47.150
Try to engage that person.

00:17:47.150 --> 00:17:50.910
But bring it down to the
lowest common denominator.

00:17:50.910 --> 00:17:54.730
The whizzes in the room will
try to bring you back up,

00:17:54.730 --> 00:17:56.314
but always try to
remember there's

00:17:56.314 --> 00:17:57.980
one or two people who
may not understand

00:17:57.980 --> 00:18:00.880
what you're talking about.

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:04.060
Joe's already
covered 10, 20, 30.

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:06.520
But really, 20 minutes.

00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:07.080
20 minutes?

00:18:07.080 --> 00:18:09.290
They gave me an hour.

00:18:09.290 --> 00:18:12.000
Why do I need to make
this a 20-minute pitch?

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.530
Well, for two reasons.

00:18:14.530 --> 00:18:16.040
One, they're going
to have trouble--

00:18:16.040 --> 00:18:18.330
you're going to have trouble
getting your presentation

00:18:18.330 --> 00:18:20.580
to work with the AV equipment.

00:18:20.580 --> 00:18:22.450
That's going to
eat up some time.

00:18:22.450 --> 00:18:25.010
But realistically, you're
going to be interrupted

00:18:25.010 --> 00:18:26.860
over and over and over again.

00:18:26.860 --> 00:18:30.420
People will drag you
into minutia and detail.

00:18:30.420 --> 00:18:32.840
You need to fight
that and resist that,

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:34.530
but you'll be stopped.

00:18:34.530 --> 00:18:38.700
And you'll never get through
your 20-minute pitch.

00:18:38.700 --> 00:18:40.420
That hour will go
just like that.

00:18:40.420 --> 00:18:43.820
So you really have to make it,
if you're pitching it alone

00:18:43.820 --> 00:18:46.320
in a room, no more
than 20 minutes.

00:18:46.320 --> 00:18:50.000
It will expand to the full hour.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.720
Use pictures.

00:18:52.720 --> 00:18:54.300
Seriously, use pictures.

00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:56.400
There's nothing more boring
than this right here.

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:03.620
There's always
somebody in the room,

00:19:03.620 --> 00:19:07.790
whether it's angels or a
venture capital partnership,

00:19:07.790 --> 00:19:11.460
someone in the room who
wants to show off they

00:19:11.460 --> 00:19:13.220
know more than you do.

00:19:13.220 --> 00:19:14.640
That's not going to work.

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:16.150
We did that three years ago.

00:19:16.150 --> 00:19:18.050
It was a failure.

00:19:18.050 --> 00:19:21.990
Or, wait a minute.

00:19:21.990 --> 00:19:23.890
The neural resistance,
I thought was

00:19:23.890 --> 00:19:25.150
going to be higher than that.

00:19:25.150 --> 00:19:26.970
You need to defend that.

00:19:26.970 --> 00:19:31.440
You're always going to be
teased into a rat hole.

00:19:31.440 --> 00:19:32.992
Here, follow me
into this rat hole,

00:19:32.992 --> 00:19:34.700
let's run around,
waste everybody's time,

00:19:34.700 --> 00:19:37.150
and then you're going
to be asked to leave.

00:19:37.150 --> 00:19:39.140
Don't fall for that.

00:19:39.140 --> 00:19:41.410
You have two options.

00:19:41.410 --> 00:19:51.240
You either firmly and with a
nice, reasonable answer, say,

00:19:51.240 --> 00:19:55.320
nope that's not the
case, and this is why,

00:19:55.320 --> 00:19:57.760
but I'll get back to that
later if you want to.

00:19:57.760 --> 00:20:05.000
Or you say, good point, I'm
not familiar with that point

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:06.210
you just made.

00:20:06.210 --> 00:20:07.680
I'll get back to you later.

00:20:07.680 --> 00:20:10.190
Don't let them continue
that conversation.

00:20:10.190 --> 00:20:13.240
You've got to know how to
shut off the questions,

00:20:13.240 --> 00:20:14.900
shut off the
spigot, and move on,

00:20:14.900 --> 00:20:19.000
because you have an
agenda to get to asking

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:20.630
for money at the very end.

00:20:20.630 --> 00:20:23.030
If you don't get to
that, then it was a nice,

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:25.270
thank you for the
information, there's the door.

00:20:25.270 --> 00:20:27.410
You have to be able
to get to that.

00:20:27.410 --> 00:20:36.210
So as important as
anything I've talked about

00:20:36.210 --> 00:20:42.880
is the need for you to
be a competent presenter.

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:47.340
You need to show passion,
you have to show confidence,

00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:50.990
and you have to
engage the audience.

00:20:50.990 --> 00:20:56.650
Not easy to do, and it takes,
sometimes, years and years

00:20:56.650 --> 00:20:58.830
to learn how to do that.

00:20:58.830 --> 00:21:01.570
It's very difficult. If I
were to grab any one of you

00:21:01.570 --> 00:21:04.040
down here and say, please give
a presentation on whatever

00:21:04.040 --> 00:21:06.065
your most passionate
thing is, you're

00:21:06.065 --> 00:21:07.440
going to be kind
of hard-pressed,

00:21:07.440 --> 00:21:10.900
you're going to want to kind
of recite things from memory,

00:21:10.900 --> 00:21:12.980
and forget about the engagement.

00:21:12.980 --> 00:21:15.680
You're going to speak too fast.

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:18.100
It's almost impossible
to speak too slowly,

00:21:18.100 --> 00:21:21.290
especially if you're from
a technical background.

00:21:21.290 --> 00:21:23.630
Slow the pace down.

00:21:23.630 --> 00:21:26.760
Make sure everybody's
keeping up with you.

00:21:26.760 --> 00:21:29.700
See if you've lost eye contact.

00:21:29.700 --> 00:21:33.010
If you have, focus on the person
who you lost eye contact with

00:21:33.010 --> 00:21:36.970
and say, I must
be confusing you.

00:21:36.970 --> 00:21:39.070
Can I answer any
question you've got?

00:21:39.070 --> 00:21:41.050
You've got to pull people out.

00:21:41.050 --> 00:21:44.740
You've got to get everybody
in the room along with you

00:21:44.740 --> 00:21:47.944
nodding their heads, because
the more they nod their head

00:21:47.944 --> 00:21:50.360
and agreeing with you, the
more likely at the end, and all

00:21:50.360 --> 00:21:53.770
I want is $25
million, and I'm going

00:21:53.770 --> 00:21:56.410
to give you 10% of my company.

00:21:56.410 --> 00:21:57.770
It's a great deal.

00:21:57.770 --> 00:22:00.770
So seriously, that's
like sales 101.

00:22:00.770 --> 00:22:02.760
Get them nodding their heads.

00:22:02.760 --> 00:22:04.860
Look at everybody in the eye.

00:22:04.860 --> 00:22:09.330
Be bold, be confident, use
passion, change your pitch

00:22:09.330 --> 00:22:13.180
and elevation, do whatever
you have to do-- histrionics,

00:22:13.180 --> 00:22:14.190
get their attention.

00:22:14.190 --> 00:22:15.730
Focus them on what
you're saying.

00:22:21.300 --> 00:22:25.080
So Joe has basically
covered the elements.

00:22:25.080 --> 00:22:26.540
And this isn't the right order.

00:22:26.540 --> 00:22:30.690
This isn't maybe Joe's order
fir a business plan or even

00:22:30.690 --> 00:22:33.400
a pitch, but basically, you
want to have these things.

00:22:33.400 --> 00:22:36.550
You want to have the hook.

00:22:36.550 --> 00:22:40.050
The hook as to be an
exciting statement.

00:22:40.050 --> 00:22:42.670
You know, hey, I
think we did fusion.

00:22:42.670 --> 00:22:43.860
It's in my basement.

00:22:43.860 --> 00:22:44.770
What?

00:22:44.770 --> 00:22:47.030
Then talk about it.

00:22:47.030 --> 00:22:49.480
Then you need to
have your solution.

00:22:49.480 --> 00:22:51.950
Your solution is, we
have a great product.

00:22:51.950 --> 00:22:54.807
It's using this technology,
using all these things

00:22:54.807 --> 00:22:55.723
in the elevator pitch.

00:22:58.870 --> 00:23:00.680
Not everybody will
agree with my order,

00:23:00.680 --> 00:23:03.150
but this is the order I like.

00:23:03.150 --> 00:23:04.360
What's your magic?

00:23:04.360 --> 00:23:08.850
Don't wait to talk about the
technology at the very end,

00:23:08.850 --> 00:23:10.450
and don't do it right up front.

00:23:10.450 --> 00:23:14.420
Hey, we solved
this implant issue.

00:23:14.420 --> 00:23:16.331
Talk about why it's
exciting, what's

00:23:16.331 --> 00:23:18.330
the market, what problem
are you going to solve,

00:23:18.330 --> 00:23:20.540
and we did it with
this unbelievably

00:23:20.540 --> 00:23:24.200
great new technology,
fresh out of the labs.

00:23:24.200 --> 00:23:25.480
Or wherever it came from.

00:23:25.480 --> 00:23:28.420
Or a new chip or whatever it is.

00:23:28.420 --> 00:23:30.134
Talk about the magic
and technology,

00:23:30.134 --> 00:23:32.550
so the technologists can get
excited and go, yes, what are

00:23:32.550 --> 00:23:35.390
you going to do with it now?

00:23:35.390 --> 00:23:38.220
Then go into the
business model, and then

00:23:38.220 --> 00:23:41.550
more detail, the
marketing and sales issue.

00:23:41.550 --> 00:23:43.570
You really have to
have a credible way

00:23:43.570 --> 00:23:45.070
to sell what you've got.

00:23:45.070 --> 00:23:49.910
You've got to have a credible
way to channel it or retail it

00:23:49.910 --> 00:23:52.030
into the customer's hands.

00:23:52.030 --> 00:23:54.260
How are you going to
be successful at that?

00:23:54.260 --> 00:23:56.880
There's a lot of great
products that need

00:23:56.880 --> 00:23:58.830
to be sold through Home Depot.

00:23:58.830 --> 00:24:03.700
And Home Depot has thousands
of these ideas coming in,

00:24:03.700 --> 00:24:06.777
and then they, one by one,
nope, no time for you, go away.

00:24:06.777 --> 00:24:08.610
Nope, no, and then what
are you going to do,

00:24:08.610 --> 00:24:10.890
with all of your channel
strategies closed off?

00:24:10.890 --> 00:24:13.120
Have a credible
solution for that.

00:24:13.120 --> 00:24:14.870
Talk about the competition.

00:24:14.870 --> 00:24:19.980
If it's a new product,
never been sold before,

00:24:19.980 --> 00:24:21.990
well, that could
be nice, but you've

00:24:21.990 --> 00:24:25.520
got to spend a huge
amount of money and time

00:24:25.520 --> 00:24:28.925
and your personal capital
creating a new niche,

00:24:28.925 --> 00:24:31.050
or a new market for this.

00:24:31.050 --> 00:24:32.540
You don't know how hard that is.

00:24:32.540 --> 00:24:33.748
It's going to be really hard.

00:24:33.748 --> 00:24:35.590
If nobody's buying
this sort of thing now,

00:24:35.590 --> 00:24:38.340
you have to-- look
at Dean Kamen.

00:24:38.340 --> 00:24:39.750
The Segway.

00:24:39.750 --> 00:24:41.450
Remember everybody
got all excited?

00:24:41.450 --> 00:24:44.520
I mean, my home in Boulder,
we had activists saying,

00:24:44.520 --> 00:24:48.110
we don't want Segways
riding down my sidewalk.

00:24:48.110 --> 00:24:50.550
And they had protests.

00:24:50.550 --> 00:24:52.620
Dean didn't realize
how hard it was

00:24:52.620 --> 00:24:57.240
to create a whole new market
where the whole country stops

00:24:57.240 --> 00:24:58.680
driving and uses Segways.

00:24:58.680 --> 00:25:00.210
It didn't work at all that way.

00:25:00.210 --> 00:25:05.310
He was trying to create a whole
new approach towards travel.

00:25:05.310 --> 00:25:08.700
Very difficult. If it's a
substitution, then who are we

00:25:08.700 --> 00:25:10.787
substituting against
and why are you better?

00:25:10.787 --> 00:25:13.120
Because we're 10 times cheaper,
faster, better, smaller.

00:25:13.120 --> 00:25:16.100
All those sorts of things.

00:25:16.100 --> 00:25:21.210
And I have management
here, not at the top.

00:25:21.210 --> 00:25:22.700
Why?

00:25:22.700 --> 00:25:27.140
Because I don't care who
you are unless I really

00:25:27.140 --> 00:25:30.080
am excited about
your ideas, and then

00:25:30.080 --> 00:25:32.020
I want to know who you are.

00:25:32.020 --> 00:25:33.550
Where'd you were
to come from, how

00:25:33.550 --> 00:25:36.960
do I know you've got to take
my money and spend it wisely?

00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:39.270
Have you done this before?

00:25:39.270 --> 00:25:41.250
Then give me all
your credentials,

00:25:41.250 --> 00:25:45.250
but not until I'm
greedy, because I

00:25:45.250 --> 00:25:49.360
want some of your stock,
please, and now, who are you

00:25:49.360 --> 00:25:51.900
and what's your team?

00:25:51.900 --> 00:25:53.600
| at that point it's credible.

00:25:53.600 --> 00:25:55.840
If you hit them too soon
with here I am an all

00:25:55.840 --> 00:25:59.840
that, without knowing whether
they're excited or greedy yet,

00:25:59.840 --> 00:26:01.570
they're going to
not listen to it.

00:26:01.570 --> 00:26:05.130
I won't listen to it
I'm going to skip it.

00:26:05.130 --> 00:26:08.090
Then go over your financials.

00:26:08.090 --> 00:26:10.950
What are you going to do
with the money that you get?

00:26:10.950 --> 00:26:12.240
How are you going to spend it?

00:26:12.240 --> 00:26:15.680
Is it a credible timeline you
have for spending that money,

00:26:15.680 --> 00:26:18.840
or are you going to
run out of money?

00:26:18.840 --> 00:26:20.340
Which is a problem,
because then you

00:26:20.340 --> 00:26:22.860
have to stop what you're doing
and go raise money sooner,

00:26:22.860 --> 00:26:26.380
than later, and
stop the company.

00:26:26.380 --> 00:26:28.244
Then go over your status
and your timeline.

00:26:28.244 --> 00:26:29.410
Have you built anything yet?

00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:30.360
Do you have any prototypes?

00:26:30.360 --> 00:26:31.600
When are you going
to have it done?

00:26:31.600 --> 00:26:33.475
How do you know you're
going to have it done?

00:26:33.475 --> 00:26:35.530
Is it a credible timeline?

00:26:35.530 --> 00:26:39.480
What people have you lined
up to build this thing?

00:26:39.480 --> 00:26:40.990
Status and timeline.

00:26:40.990 --> 00:26:46.310
And then don't forget-- a
lot of people forget this,

00:26:46.310 --> 00:26:50.000
at the very end, the offer.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:51.810
You have to make the offer.

00:26:51.810 --> 00:26:53.770
What is that offer?

00:26:53.770 --> 00:26:56.847
And for all this cool
stuff, and the $100 million

00:26:56.847 --> 00:26:58.680
we're going to make
over the next five years

00:26:58.680 --> 00:27:00.800
with this product,
I'm going to give you

00:27:00.800 --> 00:27:03.320
10% of my company
for $25 million.

00:27:03.320 --> 00:27:08.240
And we're looking at
closing in the next 60 days,

00:27:08.240 --> 00:27:12.390
and oh, by the way, we're
talking to four other venture

00:27:12.390 --> 00:27:15.956
capitalists and three of
them are quite interested.

00:27:15.956 --> 00:27:17.080
Love to hear back from you.

00:27:17.080 --> 00:27:21.780
Make the request, which is the
offer of your stock for money.

00:27:25.920 --> 00:27:27.740
A little bit about the hook.

00:27:27.740 --> 00:27:31.150
When you very first
meet somebody,

00:27:31.150 --> 00:27:35.770
you've got about seven
seconds to engage,

00:27:35.770 --> 00:27:38.170
to make them excited about
hearing the rest of what

00:27:38.170 --> 00:27:39.410
you have to say.

00:27:39.410 --> 00:27:45.910
So that hook could be
whatever the cool part

00:27:45.910 --> 00:27:49.360
of your technology or
product is going to be.

00:27:49.360 --> 00:27:52.540
The hook could be-- imagine
a safe rubber coding

00:27:52.540 --> 00:27:54.482
that conducts electricity.

00:27:54.482 --> 00:27:56.690
Wait a minute, why would I
need-- well, before I say,

00:27:56.690 --> 00:27:59.190
but how do you--
OK, keep talking.

00:27:59.190 --> 00:28:00.360
So that's a hook.

00:28:00.360 --> 00:28:03.340
An example of a hook.

00:28:03.340 --> 00:28:04.640
Have you ever felt threatened?

00:28:04.640 --> 00:28:07.620
Wow, what kind of a question--
yes, of course I have.

00:28:07.620 --> 00:28:09.350
Are you threatening me?

00:28:09.350 --> 00:28:10.778
No, we have a solution for you.

00:28:15.010 --> 00:28:18.990
Our box is 10 times smaller,
faster, cheaper, better

00:28:18.990 --> 00:28:21.570
than this.

00:28:21.570 --> 00:28:23.900
Oh, cool, the next
generation of that.

00:28:23.900 --> 00:28:27.900
People will want that.

00:28:27.900 --> 00:28:31.370
Anyway, that's kind of a hook.

00:28:31.370 --> 00:28:33.750
So think about
what is your hook?

00:28:33.750 --> 00:28:37.940
What is your bold
statement that's

00:28:37.940 --> 00:28:41.590
going to wake me up and stop
what I'm doing and listening

00:28:41.590 --> 00:28:46.930
to you, whether it's an elevator
or the beginning of a pitch.

00:28:46.930 --> 00:28:53.270
So no geek speak.

00:28:53.270 --> 00:28:55.567
No geek speak.

00:28:55.567 --> 00:28:56.400
What does that mean?

00:29:00.450 --> 00:29:02.190
I've had lots and
lots of pitches,

00:29:02.190 --> 00:29:05.900
and they start off
with technical jargon.

00:29:05.900 --> 00:29:07.290
And that's the
wrong thing to do,

00:29:07.290 --> 00:29:11.200
because then my job is
now, pull out of you,

00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:13.960
why am I greedy about that?

00:29:13.960 --> 00:29:17.330
You need to explain it simply.

00:29:17.330 --> 00:29:18.520
This is a real example.

00:29:18.520 --> 00:29:20.480
"Our technology is the first
integrated automatic book

00:29:20.480 --> 00:29:22.520
scanner that will scan and
digitize bound documents

00:29:22.520 --> 00:29:24.603
at a speed of 1,200 pages
per minute at a fraction

00:29:24.603 --> 00:29:26.025
of the cost of
existing solutions,

00:29:26.025 --> 00:29:28.400
based on destructive digital
imaging technology initially

00:29:28.400 --> 00:29:31.160
developed at Bell Labs"-- Bell
Labs isn't around anymore--

00:29:31.160 --> 00:29:34.050
"and protected by 12 patents."

00:29:34.050 --> 00:29:39.470
That's the wrong way to start a
pitch about what you're doing.

00:29:39.470 --> 00:29:43.720
A better approach is, we enable
massive knowledge sharing.

00:29:43.720 --> 00:29:47.400
We're going to digitize
all the physical libraries

00:29:47.400 --> 00:29:50.770
at an incredibly low cost,
and there's people lined up

00:29:50.770 --> 00:29:53.430
who want this technology.

00:29:53.430 --> 00:29:57.660
So that's what I
mean by geek speak.

00:29:57.660 --> 00:29:58.620
Focus of the pitch.

00:30:01.570 --> 00:30:06.660
So again, it's really tempting
to talk about the technology

00:30:06.660 --> 00:30:11.690
improvements, or
the technology that

00:30:11.690 --> 00:30:16.000
is going into your product,
and how exciting it is,

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:18.880
but you've got to convert that
into something that customers

00:30:18.880 --> 00:30:20.220
really will care about.

00:30:20.220 --> 00:30:22.500
So talk about the
customer benefits, not

00:30:22.500 --> 00:30:24.200
the tech benefits.

00:30:24.200 --> 00:30:27.090
The tech benefits-- if you
talk about the tech benefits,

00:30:27.090 --> 00:30:28.090
it's a so what?

00:30:28.090 --> 00:30:31.060
Why do I care about this
next generation of thing

00:30:31.060 --> 00:30:32.950
that you're building
or producing?

00:30:32.950 --> 00:30:35.580
It has to have benefits
for the customer.

00:30:35.580 --> 00:30:38.220
If it's telecom improved
network utilization,

00:30:38.220 --> 00:30:40.010
this is scalable and adaptable.

00:30:40.010 --> 00:30:42.790
It integrates well,
seamless integration.

00:30:42.790 --> 00:30:47.230
The figures of merit that
a buyer are interested in,

00:30:47.230 --> 00:30:49.660
not just the fact that this
is a cool next generation

00:30:49.660 --> 00:30:51.807
technology.

00:30:51.807 --> 00:30:54.140
And then you've got to talk
about the business benefits.

00:30:54.140 --> 00:30:59.290
And the business benefit--
every business has pain,

00:30:59.290 --> 00:31:02.160
and you have to find
what the pain point is.

00:31:02.160 --> 00:31:05.070
You're in pain.

00:31:05.070 --> 00:31:07.000
I can heal your pain.

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:11.010
I have something that's going
to make things better for you.

00:31:11.010 --> 00:31:14.020
And it usually has to
boil down to a dollar.

00:31:14.020 --> 00:31:20.670
You have pain that's costing you
$700,000 a year in something,

00:31:20.670 --> 00:31:24.260
and my product, my
device, my process,

00:31:24.260 --> 00:31:27.660
whatever you're selling
can cut that in half,

00:31:27.660 --> 00:31:29.260
and I can prove it to you.

00:31:29.260 --> 00:31:31.320
So that's a pain point.

00:31:31.320 --> 00:31:34.210
Increase revenues
or decrease costs.

00:31:34.210 --> 00:31:38.710
Everything's got to
boil down to a dollar.

00:31:38.710 --> 00:31:39.240
A dollar.

00:31:39.240 --> 00:31:43.480
Your technology
is not important.

00:31:43.480 --> 00:31:47.820
It's what that can do for a
business or a customer that

00:31:47.820 --> 00:31:52.240
can reduce their pain, and
that's usually evidenced

00:31:52.240 --> 00:31:54.770
by costing them money.

00:31:54.770 --> 00:31:58.160
And you're either going to make
them money or save them money.

00:32:03.030 --> 00:32:05.810
Style.

00:32:05.810 --> 00:32:08.540
If you're making a
pitch, either you've

00:32:08.540 --> 00:32:10.470
got to be the best
presenter of your team,

00:32:10.470 --> 00:32:12.280
or find the best
presenter of your team

00:32:12.280 --> 00:32:13.860
and let that person do it.

00:32:13.860 --> 00:32:18.770
It's best if the founder
or the CEO does it.

00:32:18.770 --> 00:32:22.490
I haven't seen a
whole lot of companies

00:32:22.490 --> 00:32:25.570
that aren't led by the founder
or the CEO making the pitch.

00:32:25.570 --> 00:32:30.030
So between the two of you,
unless you're the same person,

00:32:30.030 --> 00:32:31.500
get good at making the pitch.

00:32:31.500 --> 00:32:32.425
Be the best presenter.

00:32:35.860 --> 00:32:37.930
If you're not the
egghead, have the egghead

00:32:37.930 --> 00:32:42.640
in the room on a
really short leash.

00:32:42.640 --> 00:32:45.280
Because they're going to
get into the rat holes.

00:32:45.280 --> 00:32:46.950
They love rat holes.

00:32:46.950 --> 00:32:48.020
I love a rat hole.

00:32:48.020 --> 00:32:50.700
I have to sometimes wake up and
go, stop talking about that.

00:32:50.700 --> 00:32:54.100
You're excited about
it, nobody else is.

00:32:54.100 --> 00:32:58.170
But be prepared to ask the
one-off technical question.

00:32:58.170 --> 00:33:02.390
Exactly what frequency
will that resonate?

00:33:02.390 --> 00:33:04.136
Tell them.

00:33:04.136 --> 00:33:07.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:07.300 --> 00:33:08.660
I said this earlier.

00:33:08.660 --> 00:33:13.240
Give firm answers, even if
you don't have the answer.

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:16.600
Don't sound hesitant, like,
oh we hadn't thought of that.

00:33:20.160 --> 00:33:21.860
Crushing defeat.

00:33:21.860 --> 00:33:25.030
If you don't have an answer,
say, let me get back to you.

00:33:25.030 --> 00:33:26.690
I'll get back to
you in 24 hours.

00:33:26.690 --> 00:33:29.060
I think I know the answer.

00:33:29.060 --> 00:33:33.020
Or the answer is, yes of course,
we've always been that way

00:33:33.020 --> 00:33:36.710
and we always will, or
no, that's not a problem,

00:33:36.710 --> 00:33:37.660
and here is why.

00:33:37.660 --> 00:33:40.630
Be firm in your
answer, smile, I mean,

00:33:40.630 --> 00:33:46.296
don't get angry, smile, and
say yes or no, but be firm.

00:33:46.296 --> 00:33:49.070
Have the presence
to be confident,

00:33:49.070 --> 00:33:51.734
because you're asking
for their money,

00:33:51.734 --> 00:33:53.150
and they want to
give it to people

00:33:53.150 --> 00:33:57.340
who are firm and confident
and all those nice things.

00:33:57.340 --> 00:34:00.190
I talked about looking
at everybody in the room.

00:34:00.190 --> 00:34:01.366
Try to grab their eyeballs.

00:34:04.830 --> 00:34:06.930
Practice that.

00:34:06.930 --> 00:34:08.780
By the way, if you've
never given a speech

00:34:08.780 --> 00:34:11.840
in front of a large
audience, the best confidence

00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:15.960
builder before you start the
speech is, look at everybody

00:34:15.960 --> 00:34:20.699
in the room beforehand, at the
bottom or wherever you are,

00:34:20.699 --> 00:34:22.949
look at everybody in
the room, and pretend

00:34:22.949 --> 00:34:25.510
like they're an old buddy.

00:34:25.510 --> 00:34:27.110
They're an old friend.

00:34:27.110 --> 00:34:31.230
And you won't any trouble
with confidence or locking up

00:34:31.230 --> 00:34:32.480
or things like that.

00:34:32.480 --> 00:34:34.310
Try it.

00:34:34.310 --> 00:34:35.920
Do your homework,
like I said earlier.

00:34:35.920 --> 00:34:38.080
Know who you're talking to.

00:34:38.080 --> 00:34:40.190
And practice your pitch.

00:34:40.190 --> 00:34:42.330
Practice it.

00:34:42.330 --> 00:34:44.210
Have all the points
at your fingertips.

00:34:44.210 --> 00:34:47.580
Be ready to go over
them at any time.

00:34:47.580 --> 00:34:52.100
And then pull questions
out of the quiet people.

00:34:52.100 --> 00:34:55.940
Even if, you can tell, this
person does not like me

00:34:55.940 --> 00:34:59.590
or what I'm doing or anybody
that I brought up here,

00:34:59.590 --> 00:35:01.630
still, pull them out.

00:35:01.630 --> 00:35:02.305
Ask questions.

00:35:02.305 --> 00:35:03.930
Because if nothing
else, you will learn

00:35:03.930 --> 00:35:05.250
what they don't like about you.

00:35:05.250 --> 00:35:07.166
They might say, well, I
don't understand that.

00:35:07.166 --> 00:35:09.637
You said that, I
don't believe it.

00:35:09.637 --> 00:35:11.470
You may not be able to
convince that person,

00:35:11.470 --> 00:35:13.210
but make sure
everybody in the room

00:35:13.210 --> 00:35:14.930
has been able to say
something, or ask

00:35:14.930 --> 00:35:20.700
them a question of these
venture capitalists.

