00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:49.450
[INAUDIBLE] kind of cool.

00:40:49.450 --> 00:40:51.930
I like that show.

00:40:51.930 --> 00:40:55.420
So that's an example
of how you get

00:40:55.420 --> 00:40:58.900
to the point, talk about why do
I care about your technology?

00:40:58.900 --> 00:41:00.970
If you have things
in your home that

00:41:00.970 --> 00:41:02.470
needs to be controlled
or automated,

00:41:02.470 --> 00:41:03.790
but they don't
talk to each other

00:41:03.790 --> 00:41:05.520
because they're from
different manufacturers,

00:41:05.520 --> 00:41:06.490
that's the solution.

00:41:06.490 --> 00:41:09.220
And he gets to
the point quickly.

00:41:09.220 --> 00:41:14.510
Here's another example of
a presentation or a pitch

00:41:14.510 --> 00:41:18.380
that we did in the year 2000
to telecommunications company.

00:41:18.380 --> 00:41:23.550
We built a box that was 10
times faster, smarter, smaller,

00:41:23.550 --> 00:41:27.800
better, than the Nortel
box, where I had just left.

00:41:27.800 --> 00:41:31.370
And this is an
example of how you

00:41:31.370 --> 00:41:34.200
might want to use
pictures and clearly

00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:38.830
talk about the superlatives
of what you're trying to sell.

00:41:38.830 --> 00:41:42.520
So talk about a big,
total addressable market.

00:41:42.520 --> 00:41:44.850
Now, remember, this
was a long time ago.

00:41:44.850 --> 00:41:48.400
In 2008, the prediction
was, this kind of technology

00:41:48.400 --> 00:41:49.570
was going to be huge.

00:41:49.570 --> 00:41:53.430
So therefore, we need a
product in that space.

00:41:53.430 --> 00:41:59.080
And why is the stuff that you're
competing against terrible?

00:41:59.080 --> 00:42:03.100
Talk about why things
are terrible today.

00:42:03.100 --> 00:42:07.000
And then talk about
why what you're selling

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:09.030
is being purchased,
and people want it,

00:42:09.030 --> 00:42:13.770
but they want it faster,
cheaper, smaller, better.

00:42:13.770 --> 00:42:17.400
And then talk about the
evolution of how your product--

00:42:17.400 --> 00:42:20.450
and how the history of
the technology, inevitably

00:42:20.450 --> 00:42:22.970
is going to lead to what
you're trying to sell.

00:42:22.970 --> 00:42:25.430
So you want to show a nice
picture showing things

00:42:25.430 --> 00:42:29.520
getting better and faster,
and more products later on.

00:42:29.520 --> 00:42:33.200
And then in our case, we're
simplifying the telephone

00:42:33.200 --> 00:42:37.100
central office, so we show how
complicated things are now,

00:42:37.100 --> 00:42:39.400
and how the picture gets
a little simpler when

00:42:39.400 --> 00:42:40.830
you buy our product.

00:42:40.830 --> 00:42:42.250
Keeping it simple.

00:42:42.250 --> 00:42:44.650
Now, all these things were
technical, kind of jargony,

00:42:44.650 --> 00:42:47.460
but the audience
we were pitching to

00:42:47.460 --> 00:42:50.650
knew it intimately,
because that was

00:42:50.650 --> 00:42:52.190
the big bubble at that time.

00:42:52.190 --> 00:42:54.840
Fiber optics and
telecommunications.

00:42:54.840 --> 00:42:56.750
And everybody knew
a lot about it.

00:42:56.750 --> 00:43:00.190
But I try to keep it even
simpler than what they might--

00:43:00.190 --> 00:43:04.060
they were being given
pitches of terribly complex,

00:43:04.060 --> 00:43:08.240
brand new protocols, new-wave
division-- experimental stuff.

00:43:08.240 --> 00:43:09.570
We kept it simple.

00:43:09.570 --> 00:43:11.630
And I think that's
one of the reasons why

00:43:11.630 --> 00:43:14.240
we had lots of customers
and we had lots of money

00:43:14.240 --> 00:43:18.000
coming in, because we
made our value proposition

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:20.248
compelling, simple, and easy.

00:43:24.470 --> 00:43:25.702
I'll talk about that later.

00:43:25.702 --> 00:43:27.035
When do you want to raise money?

00:43:30.360 --> 00:43:33.850
So you always, always,
always, always get money

00:43:33.850 --> 00:43:37.360
when you do not need money.

00:43:37.360 --> 00:43:38.890
Why?

00:43:38.890 --> 00:43:41.960
What if I just had a round not
too long ago, I got $2 million

00:43:41.960 --> 00:43:46.640
in the bank, and I'm good
for another nine months,

00:43:46.640 --> 00:43:50.560
a year, now's a good time to
start raising money again,

00:43:50.560 --> 00:43:53.680
because people who
have money don't want

00:43:53.680 --> 00:43:56.750
to give it to you under duress.

00:43:56.750 --> 00:44:00.930
If you're going to run out of
money in six months, and it

00:44:00.930 --> 00:44:03.690
takes six months
to close a deal.

00:44:03.690 --> 00:44:07.500
And assume it's going to
take six months for you

00:44:07.500 --> 00:44:10.590
to start your campaign
and close a round.

00:44:10.590 --> 00:44:13.726
If that's the case, then
by the time you close,

00:44:13.726 --> 00:44:15.350
you're going to be
almost out of money,

00:44:15.350 --> 00:44:17.760
and if somebody holds up the
deal or bargain or whatever,

00:44:17.760 --> 00:44:22.150
your company's done, or
you start laying people off

00:44:22.150 --> 00:44:23.690
and you lose all your momentum.

00:44:23.690 --> 00:44:26.270
So always start raising
your money and plan

00:44:26.270 --> 00:44:30.510
to close around at least six
months before you really need

00:44:30.510 --> 00:44:31.010
it.

00:44:34.260 --> 00:44:36.320
How do you raise money?

00:44:36.320 --> 00:44:39.120
Let's go to this VC,
oh, they said no.

00:44:39.120 --> 00:44:42.460
Let's go to that
VC, oh they said no.

00:44:42.460 --> 00:44:45.930
Do you do it serially
or in parallel?

00:44:45.930 --> 00:44:49.250
You not only have to
do it in parallel,

00:44:49.250 --> 00:44:52.400
but you have to
orchestrate it in parallel,

00:44:52.400 --> 00:44:56.590
because this is important.

00:44:56.590 --> 00:45:01.832
If you go to one or two VCs and
spend a month or so with them,

00:45:01.832 --> 00:45:03.540
and they're kind of
dragging their heels,

00:45:03.540 --> 00:45:06.342
and then you go
to the next ones,

00:45:06.342 --> 00:45:07.800
and the next ones
are saying, well,

00:45:07.800 --> 00:45:09.450
what did the first one say?

00:45:09.450 --> 00:45:10.830
Well, they're thinking about it.

00:45:10.830 --> 00:45:12.540
How long did-- OK.

00:45:12.540 --> 00:45:16.470
They see hesitancy on some other
people, some other investors'

00:45:16.470 --> 00:45:18.845
part, they're going
to make them hesitant,

00:45:18.845 --> 00:45:20.220
and all of a
sudden, everything's

00:45:20.220 --> 00:45:21.090
being strong along.

00:45:21.090 --> 00:45:22.960
Everybody's waiting
to see, well,

00:45:22.960 --> 00:45:27.150
why didn't they-- if you do
everybody at the same time,

00:45:27.150 --> 00:45:31.400
nobody knows what hand
is being dealt where,

00:45:31.400 --> 00:45:35.219
what potential partners might
be thinking, because you often

00:45:35.219 --> 00:45:36.760
don't get money from
just one person.

00:45:36.760 --> 00:45:39.720
You get it from several
venture capitalists,

00:45:39.720 --> 00:45:41.160
and they want to
team and partner.

00:45:41.160 --> 00:45:43.720
You want to create this feeding
frenzy all at the same time.

00:45:43.720 --> 00:45:46.414
Hey, did you get a
pitch by this company?

00:45:46.414 --> 00:45:47.830
They're going to
do you next week?

00:45:47.830 --> 00:45:49.770
Let's talk about them
right afterwards.

00:45:49.770 --> 00:45:51.500
They'll talk, they'll
compare notes,

00:45:51.500 --> 00:45:53.340
and you're just more
likely to end up

00:45:53.340 --> 00:45:56.090
with a really successful
high valuation

00:45:56.090 --> 00:46:01.080
if you orchestrate your pitch.

00:46:01.080 --> 00:46:02.560
Don't dribble it out.

00:46:02.560 --> 00:46:04.370
Do it all at once
at the same time,

00:46:04.370 --> 00:46:08.600
get all the feedback at the
same time, and hit it hard.

00:46:08.600 --> 00:46:14.640
Again, assume it's going to take
six months to close a round.

00:46:14.640 --> 00:46:16.490
Signal to noise.

00:46:16.490 --> 00:46:18.770
Why should they pay
attention to you?

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:21.430
You have a nice,
pretty business plan

00:46:21.430 --> 00:46:24.010
and a pitch deck, why won't
they return your calls?

00:46:24.010 --> 00:46:25.330
Because they don't know you.

00:46:25.330 --> 00:46:31.020
And most pitches come
across their desks

00:46:31.020 --> 00:46:32.600
and they throw it away.

00:46:32.600 --> 00:46:35.860
So you really need to
have a differentiator.

00:46:35.860 --> 00:46:38.580
You need to be introduced or
have somebody do something

00:46:38.580 --> 00:46:40.020
that gets their attention.

00:46:40.020 --> 00:46:44.460
Or maybe an article in
a newspaper or something

00:46:44.460 --> 00:46:46.310
like that, to get
their attention.

00:46:46.310 --> 00:46:48.180
Think about what
signal you're going

00:46:48.180 --> 00:46:51.500
to punch through the noise
that they're hearing every day,

00:46:51.500 --> 00:46:53.470
If you can be introduced
because so-and-so

00:46:53.470 --> 00:46:57.760
knows somebody in this
venture capital partnership,

00:46:57.760 --> 00:46:59.650
that's the best way.

00:46:59.650 --> 00:47:01.800
So hand out a lot of
cards, meet people

00:47:01.800 --> 00:47:06.940
go to social
networking functions

00:47:06.940 --> 00:47:09.320
where VCs and angels
are going to be.

00:47:09.320 --> 00:47:12.920
An angel is a great way to
get introduced to big money,

00:47:12.920 --> 00:47:14.300
to the venture capitalists.

00:47:14.300 --> 00:47:17.120
Because chances
are, the good ones

00:47:17.120 --> 00:47:18.536
have worked with
them before, too.

00:47:21.140 --> 00:47:25.490
Oh, you've got two good offers
from two venture capital

00:47:25.490 --> 00:47:26.300
companies.

00:47:26.300 --> 00:47:27.650
Yay!

00:47:27.650 --> 00:47:31.500
One is better than the other.

00:47:31.500 --> 00:47:34.300
One is better than the other.

00:47:34.300 --> 00:47:36.760
What should you think
about when you decide

00:47:36.760 --> 00:47:38.740
whose money should I take?

00:47:38.740 --> 00:47:40.510
Does it matter?

00:47:40.510 --> 00:47:41.510
One's a better offer.

00:47:41.510 --> 00:47:44.740
One is going to give you $25
million for 10% of the company.

00:47:44.740 --> 00:47:47.110
The other is going to
give you $25 million

00:47:47.110 --> 00:47:49.460
for 15% of the company.

00:47:49.460 --> 00:47:51.785
Hey, that's my company
you're taking there.

00:47:51.785 --> 00:47:53.900
I want that.

00:47:53.900 --> 00:47:56.210
What do you think about?

00:47:56.210 --> 00:47:58.550
Go for the best offer?

00:47:58.550 --> 00:48:00.630
It really depends.

00:48:00.630 --> 00:48:05.870
If one is a mid-level, not
so well-known venture capital

00:48:05.870 --> 00:48:10.950
company, and the other
is a super top-tier, NEA

00:48:10.950 --> 00:48:17.960
or one with a great track
record and history of getting

00:48:17.960 --> 00:48:20.680
their companies acquired,
you should probably

00:48:20.680 --> 00:48:26.120
go with the name brand because
they can make deals happen.

00:48:26.120 --> 00:48:29.810
They can bring in money
for the next round.

00:48:29.810 --> 00:48:31.270
They have a cachet.

00:48:31.270 --> 00:48:33.550
That's hard to compete with.

00:48:33.550 --> 00:48:35.300
That's my belief.

00:48:35.300 --> 00:48:39.490
And don't focus too much
on the equity dilution,

00:48:39.490 --> 00:48:44.490
because chances are,
founders and CEOs,

00:48:44.490 --> 00:48:46.550
even if you have a
highly diluted round,

00:48:46.550 --> 00:48:48.870
they don't want you to
walk away or lose interest.

00:48:48.870 --> 00:48:52.800
They're going to
re-up your percentage.

00:48:52.800 --> 00:48:56.650
So good management tends to
keep a big hunk of the company,

00:48:56.650 --> 00:48:58.890
no matter how many
rounds you go through.

00:48:58.890 --> 00:49:01.480
So don't focus too
much about dilution.

00:49:01.480 --> 00:49:05.430
It's important to focus
on it, but not too much,

00:49:05.430 --> 00:49:08.130
Anybody know what this means?

00:49:08.130 --> 00:49:14.690
C-F-I-M-I-T-Y-M. There's usually
someone who knows what that

00:49:14.690 --> 00:49:16.630
means.

00:49:16.630 --> 00:49:22.820
Cash Is More Important
Than Your Mother.

00:49:22.820 --> 00:49:25.060
Ever heard that term?

00:49:25.060 --> 00:49:28.490
Finance people use
it all the time.

00:49:28.490 --> 00:49:31.510
Cash is really,
really important.

00:49:31.510 --> 00:49:33.570
Cash flow.

00:49:33.570 --> 00:49:35.590
The fastest way to
kill your company

00:49:35.590 --> 00:49:38.020
is not pay attention
to cash flow.

00:49:38.020 --> 00:49:41.990
Wait a minute-- we have
orders pouring in like crazy.

00:49:41.990 --> 00:49:43.670
Everything's going great.

00:49:43.670 --> 00:49:46.250
What do you mean, we're dead?

00:49:46.250 --> 00:49:47.380
We have to shut the doors?

00:49:47.380 --> 00:49:50.660
Because you can go bankrupt
if you're not paying attention

00:49:50.660 --> 00:49:53.740
to cash flow, and you
need emergency debt,

00:49:53.740 --> 00:49:55.740
and you scared off the
investors from giving you

00:49:55.740 --> 00:49:58.250
a bridge loan because you
weren't paying attention

00:49:58.250 --> 00:49:59.870
to the business.

00:49:59.870 --> 00:50:05.020
So if you don't
want to hire a CFO,

00:50:05.020 --> 00:50:09.325
have a good rental-- and a lot
of startups just rent a CFO,

00:50:09.325 --> 00:50:11.200
but make sure they're
paying attention to it.

00:50:14.420 --> 00:50:16.080
Flexibility and pivots.

00:50:16.080 --> 00:50:18.810
You're not going
to end up selling

00:50:18.810 --> 00:50:22.120
the product you think you are.

00:50:22.120 --> 00:50:24.320
In fact, the company
probably is not

00:50:24.320 --> 00:50:28.450
going to be the company
you think you're building.

00:50:28.450 --> 00:50:33.110
A very large percentage, and
no one has the data statistics,

00:50:33.110 --> 00:50:38.800
but I think most startups end
up, at some point, pivoting.

00:50:38.800 --> 00:50:41.160
Pivoting a little
bit, pivoting a lot.

00:50:41.160 --> 00:50:46.050
We were going to build-- this
company, Revolve in Boulder.

00:50:46.050 --> 00:50:47.850
They came to me
and said, we want

00:50:47.850 --> 00:50:53.300
to build an internet-addressable
irrigation system.

00:50:53.300 --> 00:50:55.960
Well, OK, that's interesting.

00:50:55.960 --> 00:50:58.640
Nest is building the
thermostat, and now they're

00:50:58.640 --> 00:51:01.690
building fire alarms and
stuff, and maybe irrigation

00:51:01.690 --> 00:51:03.700
is important, too.

00:51:03.700 --> 00:51:05.240
But we talked, and
I convinced them

00:51:05.240 --> 00:51:06.900
that there is a bigger problem.

00:51:06.900 --> 00:51:10.550
And you can be the one.

00:51:10.550 --> 00:51:13.850
The ring that rules all
devices in the home.

00:51:13.850 --> 00:51:16.040
You can build this product,
because you guys are all

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:18.970
[? ex-Amber ?] people, and
you know how to do wireless,

00:51:18.970 --> 00:51:22.260
and we have seven radios in
the box and can control every

00:51:22.260 --> 00:51:24.730
protocol in the universe.

00:51:24.730 --> 00:51:26.690
You can do it!

00:51:26.690 --> 00:51:28.690
And they went and built it.

00:51:28.690 --> 00:51:29.980
They pivoted.

00:51:29.980 --> 00:51:32.990
They were building
this irrigation system.

00:51:32.990 --> 00:51:36.190
So you might end up having to do
that once or maybe even twice.

00:51:36.190 --> 00:51:37.930
Don't be afraid
of being flexible.

00:51:37.930 --> 00:51:42.540
Don't be afraid of taking
rapid customer feedback.

00:51:42.540 --> 00:51:46.710
Use the lean, Eric Ries'
lean startup methodology.

00:51:46.710 --> 00:51:48.060
Do a lot of prototypes.

00:51:48.060 --> 00:51:48.935
Show it to customers.

00:51:48.935 --> 00:51:50.143
What do you think about that?

00:51:50.143 --> 00:51:52.940
Well, I don't like the color,
or I don't like that button.

00:51:52.940 --> 00:51:55.680
Whatever it is, take
that feedback quickly,

00:51:55.680 --> 00:51:57.680
build more prototypes,
and don't be

00:51:57.680 --> 00:52:00.322
afraid to change course
in what you're building.

00:52:04.350 --> 00:52:06.640
A few more success factors.

00:52:06.640 --> 00:52:08.640
So intellectual property.

00:52:08.640 --> 00:52:11.630
I have five patents.

00:52:11.630 --> 00:52:15.240
I really don't care,
because patents have never

00:52:15.240 --> 00:52:19.720
successfully, in my experience,
or most VCs I've talked to,

00:52:19.720 --> 00:52:22.180
has never successfully
defended anything.

00:52:22.180 --> 00:52:27.240
In fact, most of
the patents that

00:52:27.240 --> 00:52:31.490
startups pull out
of universities end

00:52:31.490 --> 00:52:36.410
up being handed back later,
either because the terms are

00:52:36.410 --> 00:52:38.280
too onerous, from
the university,

00:52:38.280 --> 00:52:40.399
I want so much thousands
of dollars a year.

00:52:40.399 --> 00:52:42.190
Well, I'm going to
figure out a way how not

00:52:42.190 --> 00:52:44.140
to have to give that to you.

00:52:44.140 --> 00:52:48.120
But anyway, IP is good
and it's important,

00:52:48.120 --> 00:52:50.030
and some people who
might buy your company

00:52:50.030 --> 00:52:52.240
may say, thank you, I
would like that patent

00:52:52.240 --> 00:52:55.840
as part of my war chest
to defend this or that.

00:52:55.840 --> 00:52:57.160
It could be important.

00:52:57.160 --> 00:53:01.210
But speed is far more
important than patents.

00:53:01.210 --> 00:53:03.010
Outrun your competitors.

00:53:03.010 --> 00:53:05.620
Even if everybody
steals your idea

00:53:05.620 --> 00:53:08.310
and they're building
it right away,

00:53:08.310 --> 00:53:12.300
and they're stealing all
your intellectual property,

00:53:12.300 --> 00:53:16.390
if you beat them to the
market, first mover will win.

00:53:16.390 --> 00:53:20.050
Just be first, be
fast, be the best.

00:53:20.050 --> 00:53:25.390
So focus more on speed
than intellectual property.

00:53:25.390 --> 00:53:27.857
Think about the mission.

00:53:27.857 --> 00:53:28.690
What is the mission?

00:53:28.690 --> 00:53:31.410
Well, isn't the
mission in the pitch?

00:53:31.410 --> 00:53:34.300
No, it's really not.

00:53:34.300 --> 00:53:36.647
The mission is when you
sit down with your team

00:53:36.647 --> 00:53:38.230
and go, what are we
trying to do here?

00:53:38.230 --> 00:53:40.590
Oh, well, we want to build this
box, we want to sell a million

00:53:40.590 --> 00:53:41.150
of them.

00:53:41.150 --> 00:53:45.441
No, what are we really
trying to do here?

00:53:45.441 --> 00:53:46.190
What are we doing?

00:53:46.190 --> 00:53:48.023
Well, we want to change
the way people think

00:53:48.023 --> 00:53:52.550
about this whole field, or we
want to change the way people

00:53:52.550 --> 00:53:56.030
interface with their
home, or what is

00:53:56.030 --> 00:53:58.230
it you're really trying to do?

00:53:58.230 --> 00:54:01.820
And you're using a technology
for right now to do it,

00:54:01.820 --> 00:54:04.560
but later on you may
move on to other things.

00:54:04.560 --> 00:54:06.190
But what are you
really trying to do?

00:54:06.190 --> 00:54:08.690
Figure out your mission
statement, word for word.

00:54:08.690 --> 00:54:10.910
Figure it out.

00:54:10.910 --> 00:54:11.920
How am I doing on time?

00:54:11.920 --> 00:54:12.430
Am I out?

00:54:16.230 --> 00:54:18.530
I'm out?

00:54:18.530 --> 00:54:19.030
I'm good?

00:54:19.030 --> 00:54:21.130
OK, all right.

00:54:21.130 --> 00:54:22.120
The team.

00:54:22.120 --> 00:54:22.640
The team.

00:54:26.350 --> 00:54:29.742
Really, venture capitalists
do look at the team,

00:54:29.742 --> 00:54:31.950
and a lot of them say, yeah,
the most important thing

00:54:31.950 --> 00:54:36.780
is the team and we're
betting on the team.

00:54:36.780 --> 00:54:38.844
Well, really, they
want your idea

00:54:38.844 --> 00:54:40.010
to make them a lot of money.

00:54:40.010 --> 00:54:41.460
That's the most important thing.

00:54:41.460 --> 00:54:47.470
But the team can pivot or be
flexible and have the integrity

00:54:47.470 --> 00:54:51.620
to be able to handle
shocks, whether it's a money

00:54:51.620 --> 00:54:54.050
shock or a technology shock.

00:54:54.050 --> 00:54:57.630
Or we just came to market and
so did three other companies.

00:54:57.630 --> 00:54:58.560
What do we do now?

00:54:58.560 --> 00:55:00.940
Do we buckle or are we tough?

00:55:00.940 --> 00:55:03.290
Is this team going
to stick with it?

00:55:03.290 --> 00:55:05.090
Are we going to work
whatever we have to?

00:55:05.090 --> 00:55:06.672
The team is really important.

00:55:06.672 --> 00:55:08.380
Think about that as
you're assembling it.

00:55:08.380 --> 00:55:12.990
Make sure the chemistry works.

00:55:12.990 --> 00:55:16.890
There will be the
time when you'll

00:55:16.890 --> 00:55:19.210
have founder versus CEO issues.

00:55:19.210 --> 00:55:21.730
Who's really running this
company, or this is my baby,

00:55:21.730 --> 00:55:22.760
or whatever.

00:55:22.760 --> 00:55:25.124
Or you'll have hires of
people who you really

00:55:25.124 --> 00:55:26.540
like, but they're
not working out,

00:55:26.540 --> 00:55:28.985
and what do we do with them?

00:55:28.985 --> 00:55:31.590
These things have to be
thought out well in advance.

00:55:31.590 --> 00:55:33.620
You have to be able to
make the tough decisions.

00:55:33.620 --> 00:55:35.380
And part of that
toughness has to be

00:55:35.380 --> 00:55:37.780
displayed to the
venture capitalists,

00:55:37.780 --> 00:55:39.080
to the people giving you money.

00:55:39.080 --> 00:55:40.830
Yet you have to have
good answers for when

00:55:40.830 --> 00:55:42.380
people-- what would
you do if this

00:55:42.380 --> 00:55:44.660
were to happen with the team?

00:55:44.660 --> 00:55:45.784
Have that thought out.

00:55:51.712 --> 00:55:53.670
How much money will it
cost to build a company?

00:55:53.670 --> 00:55:55.290
That's part of
the business plan.

00:55:55.290 --> 00:55:57.674
And how much money
you will you make us?

00:56:01.190 --> 00:56:04.840
Also goes into your final exit
strategy when you go public.

00:56:07.336 --> 00:56:08.710
Think about what
happens when you

00:56:08.710 --> 00:56:11.130
go-- have a credible
story when you go public.

00:56:11.130 --> 00:56:12.930
Even if you end up
getting acquired,

00:56:12.930 --> 00:56:14.370
always plan on going public.

00:56:17.040 --> 00:56:18.240
Just a few more real quick.

00:56:22.970 --> 00:56:24.350
One of the things
about startups,

00:56:24.350 --> 00:56:25.724
if you don't have
any experience,

00:56:25.724 --> 00:56:28.220
it's really, really tough
to convince money people

00:56:28.220 --> 00:56:29.790
that you know what you're doing.

00:56:29.790 --> 00:56:33.330
So you have to surround
yourself with people who

00:56:33.330 --> 00:56:35.000
compensate for your weaknesses.

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:36.590
If you want to be
the CEO of a company

00:56:36.590 --> 00:56:38.870
but you don't have any
experience in finance or sales,

00:56:38.870 --> 00:56:43.070
whatever, this is my
team, and everybody rounds

00:56:43.070 --> 00:56:43.860
each other out.

00:56:43.860 --> 00:56:46.664
You have to make sure you
answer that issue of, are

00:56:46.664 --> 00:56:48.330
you really ready for
this startup, based

00:56:48.330 --> 00:56:51.160
on your experience level?

00:56:51.160 --> 00:56:54.120
We talked about trying to
do it again after a failure.

00:56:54.120 --> 00:56:55.300
Failure is not bad.

00:56:55.300 --> 00:56:59.670
In Silicon Valley,
it's a mark of courage.

00:56:59.670 --> 00:57:03.220
Speed and execution
are personality traits.

00:57:03.220 --> 00:57:05.070
They really are.

00:57:05.070 --> 00:57:07.569
If you don't come
across as high energy,

00:57:07.569 --> 00:57:09.110
I'm going to be a
hard time believing

00:57:09.110 --> 00:57:11.390
that you have this as
a personality trait,

00:57:11.390 --> 00:57:15.190
that you are going to get this
product done fast when you

00:57:15.190 --> 00:57:16.310
say it's going to be done.

00:57:16.310 --> 00:57:19.540
You're willing to put in the
late midnight oil, burning that

00:57:19.540 --> 00:57:22.060
to get this thing out the door.

00:57:22.060 --> 00:57:25.630
Try to convey that you're
capable of these things.

00:57:25.630 --> 00:57:27.630
Focus, focus, focus.

00:57:27.630 --> 00:57:30.630
The worst thing that
can happen to a startup

00:57:30.630 --> 00:57:33.850
is, OK we started
out building this,

00:57:33.850 --> 00:57:37.410
but oh, here's a shiny, pretty
little thing over there.

00:57:37.410 --> 00:57:39.600
And I'm going to start
going build that.

00:57:39.600 --> 00:57:40.440
Oh, wait a minute.

00:57:40.440 --> 00:57:43.370
I just read about
that, it's cool, too.

00:57:43.370 --> 00:57:45.440
That's losing focus.

00:57:45.440 --> 00:57:49.710
Sometimes you're going to be
forced to pivot because there's

00:57:49.710 --> 00:57:52.342
a major block that you
didn't expect thrown up

00:57:52.342 --> 00:57:54.300
in front of you, and you
need to get around it.

00:57:54.300 --> 00:57:57.600
You need to pivot around it and
move on to something similar,

00:57:57.600 --> 00:58:00.880
but you don't want to give
up one perfectly good thing

00:58:00.880 --> 00:58:04.380
that you spent six months doing
just because something else

00:58:04.380 --> 00:58:06.740
nicer and prettier came along.

00:58:06.740 --> 00:58:07.800
So focus.

00:58:07.800 --> 00:58:08.950
You have to stay focused.

00:58:08.950 --> 00:58:12.062
If somebody says, hey
boss, look at this.

00:58:12.062 --> 00:58:13.270
They just came out with that.

00:58:13.270 --> 00:58:14.860
Shouldn't we be building that?

00:58:14.860 --> 00:58:16.380
Focus.

00:58:16.380 --> 00:58:17.971
We're getting this done now.

00:58:17.971 --> 00:58:19.720
We're going to work
on it and that's that.

00:58:23.120 --> 00:58:26.180
We talked about stock
dilution and control,

00:58:26.180 --> 00:58:28.470
and not to worry
too much about that.

00:58:28.470 --> 00:58:30.470
And then finally, take
help from your investors.

00:58:33.090 --> 00:58:37.360
But investors probably aren't
going to be very helpful.

00:58:37.360 --> 00:58:40.030
You might think they are,
they might tell you they are,

00:58:40.030 --> 00:58:41.900
they're going to say
we're your buddies,

00:58:41.900 --> 00:58:44.730
I love what you're doing, I
love you, I'm going to help you,

00:58:44.730 --> 00:58:48.030
I'm going to roll up my
sleeves, and it's all BS.

00:58:48.030 --> 00:58:49.116
They can't.

00:58:49.116 --> 00:58:50.490
They're doing too
many companies.

00:58:50.490 --> 00:58:53.010
They're sitting
on too many boards

00:58:53.010 --> 00:58:54.330
They know people.

00:58:54.330 --> 00:58:56.950
Use the network and
use their connections.

00:58:56.950 --> 00:58:59.950
At the next round,
have them help you.

00:58:59.950 --> 00:59:03.710
Who you're partnering with now,
can we parade in front of them

00:59:03.710 --> 00:59:04.670
as well?

00:59:04.670 --> 00:59:06.900
But they're not going
to help you that much.

00:59:06.900 --> 00:59:09.820
Angel investors are more
likely to roll their sleeves up

00:59:09.820 --> 00:59:12.820
because sometimes they're
retirees like me who

00:59:12.820 --> 00:59:16.790
want to have fun and play with
gadgets and stuff like that,

00:59:16.790 --> 00:59:17.810
and they could help.

00:59:17.810 --> 00:59:21.100
But in general, the kind
of help from your investors

00:59:21.100 --> 00:59:22.840
is more who they know.

00:59:22.840 --> 00:59:24.790
Customers and
networks and partners.

00:59:27.340 --> 00:59:31.400
OK, so the bottom line is,
this all really boils down

00:59:31.400 --> 00:59:32.250
to leadership.

00:59:32.250 --> 00:59:35.230
Whether it's technology
leadership, CEO leadership,

00:59:35.230 --> 00:59:39.500
team management, you want to be
the leader in whatever you do.

00:59:39.500 --> 00:59:42.520
So leadership wins.

00:59:42.520 --> 00:59:46.980
In order to be a leader,
you've got to show passion,

00:59:46.980 --> 00:59:51.970
you've got to be confident,
and you have to engage.

00:59:51.970 --> 00:59:54.880
You have to do
those three things.

00:59:54.880 --> 00:59:57.160
You need to have
a call to action.

00:59:57.160 --> 00:59:58.500
I'm going to go do this.

00:59:58.500 --> 01:00:00.310
Do you want to be a part of it?

01:00:00.310 --> 01:00:03.000
I can give you a
piece of my company.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:04.940
Love to have you
on board, but we're

01:00:04.940 --> 01:00:06.530
going to change the world.

01:00:06.530 --> 01:00:09.500
You need to make
that pitch and then

01:00:09.500 --> 01:00:12.880
you win the war, even if
you don't win that battle,

01:00:12.880 --> 01:00:15.390
even if you don't get that VC.

01:00:15.390 --> 01:00:17.484
The word will get out,
what you're trying to do,

01:00:17.484 --> 01:00:18.650
and you're going to do fine.

01:00:26.044 --> 01:00:27.384
[APPLAUSE]

01:00:27.384 --> 01:00:28.550
MODERATOR: Thank you, Steve.

01:00:28.550 --> 01:00:29.630
STEPHEN PEARSE: Thanks, Joe.

01:00:29.630 --> 01:00:30.320
Thank you, guys.

01:00:30.320 --> 01:00:35.470
And by the way, all of you can
be the next Tony Stark or Betty

01:00:35.470 --> 01:00:36.570
Stark.

01:00:36.570 --> 01:00:39.890
We need another Tony
Stark, a female Tony Stark,

01:00:39.890 --> 01:00:40.930
captain of industry.

01:00:40.930 --> 01:00:42.127
So good luck, OK?

01:00:42.127 --> 01:00:42.960
Thank you very much.

01:00:42.960 --> 01:00:44.510
